Clinton &apos;s and Trump &apos;s Economic Policy Settlement : it &apos;s All about the Money
investing in infrastructure and preventing the TTP trade agreement - both Clinton and Trump want that .
however , the two US presidential candidates are divided on tax and energy policy and on a fundamental issue .
the differences in economic policy between Donald Trump and Hillary Clinton are based on a fundamental , rather philosophical , difference .
the , about the role of the state .
Trump wants to keep those in doubt rather small and warns about how the state can harm the economy - with taxes and regulations .
Clinton wants to tax the economy to death and regulate it to death , he says .
he himself would be quite different , Trump claims .
he would greatly reduce regulations , and he would argue for far @-@ reaching tax reform with lower tax rates - for individuals and for businesses .
Clinton , on the other hand , says that the state has certain tasks to perform , that it has disadvantaged opportunities and that it needs money .
that is why taxes on the rich would be increased , she says .
interestingly , both are very close to infrastructure .
they need to be invested , Trump and Clinton say almost exactly the same .
the democratic candidate even announces the biggest investment in new jobs since World War II .
government investment programs in infrastructure are classic democratic policies , and are strongly opposed , say , by Republicans &quot; statesmanship wing .
so Trump could have internal party discussions .
the differences in energy and climate policy are clearer .
Trump wants to build coal @-@ fired power plants and get coal back into the US .
oil production should also be possible in previously protected areas and the Paris climate agreement will be terminated .
Clinton , on the other hand , explicitly wants to expand renewable energies with her investment program and demands that &quot; a country will become the superpower of clean energy and create millions of jobs . &quot;
&quot; it will probably be either China , Germany or America - I want us to be . &quot;
but not only in terms of infrastructure - even in international trade agreements , the two competitors are not too far apart .
TPP , the Trans @-@ Pacific Trade Agreement , do not want to sign either .
at the same time , they do not want to isolate the US from international trade - they simply want to protect American jobs better .
for example , Clinton is calling for them to be paid better .
the current minimum wage of $ 7.25 was a hunger wage .
it wants to increase it to $ 15 per hour .
what Trump wants to do on this issue is not quite clear : once he says : the minimum wage must rise , he says that he must not be changed .
but the major debate over the coming months is likely to be more about the fiscal policies of the two camps .
on the one hand , there is Trump , who wants to relieve the economy and the citizens in order to boost growth .
his critics claim that this would only add to the budget deficit .
on the other hand , Clinton , who wants at least to ask the rich to pay more taxes , and whose critics say that more taxes are not the solution .
escape : &quot; every fleeing woman has experience of sexual violence &quot;
sexual violence is almost everyday for women fleeing alone .
when they arrive in Germany , they are often traumatised .
a house offers refuge .
four women sit in a large kitchen .
everyone has a baby with a maximum age of one year .
one has put her little son in the arm .
he looks with great eyes curious into the room .
his mother sticks on the table .
until she notices that she is observed .
she smiles briefly and kisses the little ones .
the scene seems normal .
until you talk to Katrin Bahr .
she is Managing Director of Condrobs , a provider of social assistance in Bavaria , and deals , among other things , with women fleeing .
the four women in the kitchen have fled .
they live in the north of Munich in one of the few decentralized accommodation facilities for women and their children in Bavaria .
in January , Condrobs set up the facility together with Pro Familia and the Munich women &apos;s assistance .
it was recently officially opened .
60 people live there - about 40 women and 20 children .
there are no men - even as visitors .
the exception is a guard in front of the door .
&quot; it is not exaggerated to say that every woman who comes here has had experience of sexual violence on her flight , &quot; says Bahr .
&quot; men flee for wars because they are persecuted politically , because they are threatened with torture or death , or because their families send them to Europe as a source of hope , &quot; she says .
for women , there are other reasons for escaping : &quot; many steal secretly because they see no other way out . &quot;
in their homeland they have experienced sexual violence , forced marriages , honour killings , slavery or forced prostitution .
it is continuing .
this is continuing to escape .
&quot; that smugglers , for example , demand sexual action for a bottle of water is not rare , &quot; says Bahr .
and women are alone , they are not protected by their families .
who believes that when they arrive in Germany , the end tells Bahr .
here , too , single women in refugee accommodation would often be considered inferior and , at worst , abused .
as a result , about 90 % of women living in accommodation in the north of Munich are traumatized , she estimates .
&quot; some of the children are certainly not voluntary . &quot;
many women are so accustomed to saying nothing .
&quot; or they don &apos;t dare to talk openly about the experience because the shame is too big . &quot;
because they often don &apos;t know how to help , it needs more accommodation only for them , calls Bahr .
in Bavaria , the seven district governments are responsible for accommodating refugees .
some say no to the question of whether they know about a project similar to that in Munich .
in the Oberpfalz and Oberfranken , for example , there is no such thing in government accommodation .
even in Schwaben , women who are alone are not accommodated separately , says Karl @-@ Heinz Meyer , press spokesman of the government .
in Oberbayern , Unter- und Mittelfranken there are floors or own houses for single women and their children .
the exception is Niederbayern , where there are two central accommodation exclusively for women .
the Committee on Women &apos;s Rights and Gender Equality in the European Parliament also calls for women to be kept separately from men .
in a study published for the committee , it says : &apos; it is very important that men and women are kept separately &apos; .
&quot; if there is a lack of privacy or if men and women are accommodated together , violence against women can occur - continuously . &quot;
in particular , the washing rooms should be separate and easily accessible to women , the study states .
the extent to which women feel this need for protection can be read in the sense that there is in Munich .
&quot; we have had a long waiting list , &quot; says Bahr .
you could easily open a second house .
assistant doctors strike : calls for new industrial action
deputies of assistant doctors have called on their trade union to approve new industrial action in their disputes over a new treaty .
the Junior Doctors Committee ( JDC ) of the British Medical Association ( BMA ) has called for the full advice of the Council to approve more work @-@ fighting measures from the beginning of September .
the JDC said that ministers had failed to respond to concerns about the Treaty .
assistant doctors and medical students voted in July to reject a contract agreed with the BMA .
it was rejected by 58 % of its members who voted in the elections .
in a letter to members published on Twitter on Thursday evening , JDC Chairman Ellen McCourt said that the government had remained &quot; persistent calm &quot; on issues , which led to the Treaty being rejected .
she said : &quot; in view of this , the JDC Board voted to completely reject the proposed new treaty and called for official renegotiations on all your concerns . &quot;
in response to the government &apos;s silence , the JDC Board today made a formal request for a special meeting of the BMA Council to approve an ongoing program of escalating industrial action , which begins in early September .
the disputes led to the six @-@ fold strike by assists this year , the first total shortfalls in the history of the NHS .
Dr. Johann Malawana , head of the BMA assistant physician , resigned after the election to reject the agreed terms of contract recommended by the BMA .
he informed BMA members during the meetings held before the vote by 54,000 assistants and medical students that the contract was beneficial and should be adopted .
after the vote , Health Minister Jeremy Hunt said that the contract for doctors in England would be forcibly introduced .
Russia and Turkey : an &quot; alliance of outsiders &quot; ?
it was a gesture that ended a crisis .
the leaders of Russia and Turkey met on Tuesday to give their hands and announce an official end to the eight @-@ month war of words and economic sanctions .
but when Vladimir Putin received his Turkish counterpart in the gold @-@ plated St. Petersburg Palace Hall , I cannot resist the impression that Ankara wants this reconciliation most .
there was a handshake , yes .
but Putin &apos;s smile had a shabby effect , and he had little warmth , even for his restrained circumstances .
Recep Tayyip Erdogan , on the other hand , repeatedly spoke of his &quot; dear friend &quot; Putin - five times , according to a report .
I could not count it any more .
he also promised that relations with Russia would not only return to their old pre @-@ crisis level , but would even improve .
the next day , a newspaper said that Erdogan would have behaved as if nothing had happened .
his enthusiasm seemed to me to suggest the opposite .
but a strong , sustained cooling that Putin sparked showed that Russia &apos;s leader had forgotten nothing .
rather , the cause of the crisis was the first thing he mentioned in his introductory remarks : Turkey &apos;s closure of a Russian fighter gun on the Syrian border .
Moscow &apos;s reaction at the time was cloudy .
Putin shared out , accusing Ankara of falling back on Russia .
the crime was even greater because it was committed by a supposed friend .
rebuilding the veto will be difficult , if not impossible .
public opinion in Russia has changed since November .
for months , state @-@ controlled media carried out a violent , unfettered attack on Ankara .
at one time , it seemed that the Turks were to blame for everything .
most serious were the allegations by senior officials that Erdogan &apos;s own family would have benefited from illegal oil trading in areas of Syria controlled by the so @-@ called Islamic State .
he vehemently denied this .
but in St.Petersburg , the official message was that it is time to look forward .
after all , this meeting took place only because Putin received the apology he wanted to hear from President Erdogan .
Russia could claim some sort of victory .
for Ankara , the benefits of a ceasefire are clear .
Erdogan needs , first and foremost , all the friends he can get after he was abducted in a failed coup d &apos;Ã©tat last month .
repeated terrorist attacks on Turkey have also shaken him .
but there are also economic motives .
Russian sanctions have hit Turkey hard - especially the ban on charter flights , which usually bring several million Russian tourists to the Turkish coast every year .
the number has fallen by almost 90 % .
in Russia , tour operators and charter companies will be made easier if flights are resumed .
they count on a late seasonal rush to the Mediterranean Sea .
this week , state television predicted cheaper fruit and vegetables as soon as Turkish agricultural imports are allowed .
a report in Vedemosti put it as follows : &apos; tourists there long , tomatoes here long &apos; .
but the visit had an additional political value for Moscow .
Ankara is angry with the West , considering its response to the attempted takeover as a weak response .
what is more , the persistent resentment of the snail &apos;s pace of EU accession negotiations and Putin - eager to take advantage of the cool mood and reduce Turkey &apos;s relationship with the West .
the Russian head of state certainly won a bonus in Ankara for demanding support for the elected authorities after the attempted coup .
this is a matter of course for Moscow , which itself has a deep @-@ seated fear of regime change .
the summit in this glorious palace by the sea allowed Russia and Turkey to portray , as an analyst once described , an &quot; alliance of outsiders &quot; : two countries that feel offended and badly treated by the West and are now allied .
nevertheless , despite public reconciliation , there are still major differences between the two .
the biggest difference is Syria , where Moscow recently gave itself the role of peacemaker , but where Russia and Turkey support opposing sides .
it may be significant that , after almost three hours of initial talks , both presidents declared at the press conference that they had not even drawn up the issue .
Turkey &apos;s president deliberately avoided answering a question about their differences , while Putin decided to emphasize them .
there is no clear consensus on where a common denominator can be found on Syria .
but , after months of open hostilities - and given the potential for a perfect disaster , when NATO member Turkey shot down Russia &apos;s combat jet - it is certainly better for the two leaders to talk to each other at least once again .
Royal Bank of Scotland no longer available to customers outside Scotland
according to the Bank &apos;s Chief Executive Officer , RBS will be reduced to a backoffice role .
Royal Bank of Scotland will no longer be available to customers outside Scotland .
Ross McEwan informed the BBC Scotland that RBS was linked to the Bank &apos;s global ambitions .
since then , the Bank has distanced itself when it had to be almost collapsed and saved eight years ago .
during this period , trademark strategists &quot; RBS &quot; have used to protect other end @-@ user financial brands .
she supported international sport with millions of pounds of sponsorship , from Six Nations Rugby to Wimbledon winner Andy Murray .
but now it has decided to focus more national brands .
Royal Bank of Scotland will only be available to customers in Scotland , but will not be initialized .
in England and Wales , all RSB references , decentralised headquarters and stock exchange listing will change to NatWest .
Ulster Bank is already used for customers in the Republic of Ireland and Northern Ireland .
there are other smaller brands for the retail business that will become more important - Coutts , Adam &amp; Co , Drummond and Holt &apos;s Military Bank .
McEwan was interviewed during a tour of customers and employees in Inverness @-@ shire .
he told BBC Scotland : &quot; the RSB brand will become our investor brand and the brand under which our employees will be employed , as we are now becoming more of a bank of brands . &quot;
when the bank itself became a global brand , RBS became a global brand .
I say now that we are not pursuing global objectives but local objectives .
each of these brands will stand for something completely different in their own communities and our employees will work with customers under these brands .
RBS has already said that it will no longer continue its Six Nations sponsorship and that it will increase the visibility of the various brands in its sports sponsorship .
&quot; it is time for us to become the bank of brands , because how do we focus on making it a better bank for customers ? &quot; said the CEO .
it would have been very cynical three years ago if we had said that we would be a great bank for our customers and would have launched these brands .
but with our work , the focus on customer needs and not our own , I think we will see many changes .
we can re @-@ launch these brands , so I think the time has come .
