Destination plates : who actually buys records ?
lonely middle @-@ aged men love plates .
before you rush to the comment part to overrule it under the pseudonym Non @-@ Anglo @-@ Saxon Middle Ages with harsh insults , this statement is derived from current data .
according to YouGov , the much @-@ talked resurrection of records is not due to a boom in Millennium , which wants to welcome the novelty of physical objects , but to midlife nostalgia .
those who have recently bought a record are likely to be between 45 and 54 .
indeed , the 18 @-@ 24 age group is the most unlikely buyer group .
it is also not a hordes of hobby collectors - it has an emotional meaning : older record buyers retain their feelings for themselves ( 56 % vs. 53 % ) and enjoy spending time alone ( 69 % vs. 66 % ) .
but are the results of YouGov ?
if this blog were a news report on television , the camera would follow me , while walking in the middle of a busy street in Soho , wearing a modest grey suit and stuffing wild before standing , holding my hands and saying something more decisive like : &quot; so let us take a closer look at it . &quot;
so let us look at it .
even though the heart of Sohos is slowly losing its charm - hotels , restaurants and offices now fill up the buildings where once independent sellers were established - there is still a handful of fantastic record shops .
I would probably ask the cameraman to turn off the camera for the next part in which I am close to various men in such shops and try to assess their age and mood by observing .
Stuart from Glasgow , 55 , whom I followed by Sister Ray ( data count : two young women , three middle @-@ aged men ) into Reckless Records ( data count : eight middle @-@ aged men , a woman , probably around the 20 ) , is a day for a meeting in London and goes through the shops to fill the few hours .
is he a collector , I ask ?
he says .
I have about 3,000 or 4,000 plates .
these records , shown above ( he sent me the snapshot by email , I did not follow him home ) , dress up the walls of his living room .
the reason why he has such a considerable number of albums and singles is the result of his disposable income : he is now able to buy plates that he could not afford when she appeared and again bought items he sold when he was young and embarrassed .
&quot; many things I buy are from the late 1960s , early 1970s , when I was 11 or 12 .
he agrees that those who buy plates are more introverted and like to spend time alone , and adds : &quot; I don &apos;t smoke and I don &apos;t drink much .
that is my shop .
WEZ , 25 , who works at Sister Ray , also believes that many customers who meet him will be on the YouGov profile .
however , he also noticed a new wave of people affected by the Medienhpe , people who have heard about the comeback and are forced to buy their old records again .
of the conversations I have had , people usually got rid of their collection around 1998 or 1999 .
customers who once sold their records to buy CDs now sell their CDs to buy their records , &quot; he says .
this would explain the boom of record revival supporters of a certain age .
but what about the supposed emotional meaning of plates ?
it takes only a few seconds in a business like Phonica to recognize that record stores offer a reassuring community of like @-@ minded people .
according to Wez , some of the older customers took inspiration from the contactless payment system .
some record fans feel overwhelmed by the digital world and want to retreat to the stability of familiar record covers , objects that wake up happily .
&quot; I think sometimes it can be the filling of a void or the possession of material possessions as a kind of comfort , &quot; says Wez .
that is the case with me as a collector and I think it is the case with many people .
it is an easy way to deal with it mentally .
&quot; we are like their social workers ! &quot; an employee flees from a stack .
a survey conducted by ICM in April revealed that almost 50 % of the people who bought a record last month have not yet heard them .
the survey also found that 41 % have a record player that they never use , while 7 % of those who buy a disk do not have a record player .
at this point in the news report , I would probably be very concerned , while leafing through a stack of Bossa Nova compilations .
Jonny , 42 , who works on Sounds of the Universe ( data count : three middle @-@ aged men ) , noticed a &quot; trophy aspect &quot; of the revival .
&quot; someone came here recently and said : &quot; I don &apos;t have a record player , but I would like to buy a Radiohead record so I can put it in the shelf , &quot; he says .
this is not a large percentage , but it is definitely happening .
more product @-@ oriented , less musical .
we have people who say , &quot; I have no record player . &quot;
these are younger people , not older people , who are only slowly arriving .
Fopp , which devoted almost a whole floor to the records , has a colorful audience when I go .
there are couples around 70 , tourists taking photos , teenagers and middle @-@ aged women .
even if the atmosphere is a little less relaxed than in the above mentioned shops - Wild Beasts of the latest synthesizer and sexpacked pop instead of experimental jazz , it is good to see such diversity among customers .
none of them looks rather unique , but needing mental trauma is difficult to detect if you are next to someone for 30 seconds .
Elanora , 27 , has been running in business for a few minutes and looks at the variety of plates for sale .
it is more like a showcase than a big purchase .
she does not deserve much , so collecting records is not a real option , she says .
it costs a lot .
it is easy to hear music from a computer or in other ways , but the beauty of plates is ... &quot; she drives with a beloved sigh .
I do not know how to explain it - it is really unique .
my last stop is a business that is said to have inspired a new generation of record lovers : URBAN Outfitters .
while I seem to be simulating jeans hotpants , I observe a group of young teenagers who are grouping around Polaroid cameras for a moment before a father and daughter think about buying a Crosley record player .
to the left is a staircase , a wall full of noble , Jeff Buckley , Amy Winehouse and Fleetwood Mac : a mixture of contemporary music and classics , the essential plates for an average collection .
no one looks at them - perhaps because they are just decorative , some so high that it is impossible to touch them .
it is pure &quot; record art . &quot;
but , given that any attraction for these items means more money for the industry and some customers could send to the depths of Sohos for more , there is nothing to complain .
it is no surprise that a population that has more time and money than others is also the one that spends most on luxury items like plates .
even though my research showed that the results of YouGov are correct , they do not take into account , at least in record stores in Soho , the large number of female collectors who exist in reality , record shops and online forums .
these people probably work hard in school or in offices .
they certainly do not spend their Thursday morning with the butterflies through Berwick Street &apos;s record shops and leaves through plates , while avoiding the stubborn gaze of an implacable 30 @-@ year @-@ old false moderator who rises above the shoulders of unsuspecting middle @-@ aged men .
