French Court rejects offer to demolish shops in the jungle refugee camp
a French court rejected an offer by the authorities in Calais to bring down dozens of provisional shops and restaurants in the jungle of Calais where thousands of refugees live .
in a trial this week , the authorities in Calais argued that the state should be empowered to dismantle 72 temporary shops where people sell goods , from cigarettes to energy drinks , offer hairdressing services , or sell tea for 50 cents ( 40 pence ) or simple meals for a few euros in provisional restaurants .
Calais &apos;s prefecture argued that these places should be demolished , because they would be a parallel economy , from which no taxes would be paid and which would risk fire and sanity .
humanitarian groups informed the Court that the shops and restaurants were important because the free meals offered by the state @-@ supported association and other groups would not provide sufficient food for the growing numbers in the camp .
they also pointed out that the temporary shops and restaurants would often provide accommodation and free meals for people in need .
a court in Lille ruled that there was no legal basis for expelling people who operate the 72 provisional shops , but acknowledged that the concerns of the Calais prefecture were &quot; absolutely understandable . &quot;
judge Jean @-@ FranÃ§ois Molla said that food shops , cafÃ©s , and restaurants would play a much larger role than just feeding people who &quot; live in extremely precarious conditions . &quot;
he said that the areas offer quiet meeting points between refugees and volunteers .
one of the places threatened by the low tide was the Jungle Book Kids &apos; CafÃ© of the camp , which is run by the public and offers 200 meals a day , English and French classes and advice on asylum matters for the hundreds of vulnerable , unaccompanied minors in the camp .
more than 170,000 people signed the petition to keep the Kids &apos; CafÃ© .
in a letter to the Guardian , it said that the closure &quot; would be a disaster for these children , of which the last eight years are old . &quot;
the two relief organizations Help Refugees and L &apos;Auberge des Migrants estimated on Friday that the number of people living in the jungle camp has risen to over 9,000 - the highest number so far - after a sharp increase in newcomers over the summer .
