military leadership falsifies ISIS intelligence , says Congress Committee
military personnel of the United States Central Command changed intelligence to draw a more optimistic picture of the war against the so @-@ called Islamic State in Iraq and Syria than the actual conditions on the ground would have allowed a Congress committee of inquiry to report on Thursday .
the preliminary report , prepared by a task force of Republican members of the Armed Forces Committee , secret service committees , and the Wehrmacht , reports of great dissatisfaction among Central Command intelligence analysts who reported how superiors changed their assessments of America &apos;s efforts to fight the Islamic State .
the Central Command ( Cencom ) is the military headquarters in Tampa , Florida , which controls American military operations in the Middle East and Central Asia .
&quot; intelligence @-@ related information typically obtained by high @-@ level CENTCOM commanders was regularly more positive than other intelligence services , &quot; a newspaper article quoted the report .
&quot; what happened at CENTCOM is unacceptable - our soldiers suffer when poor analyses are presented to our political leaders , &quot; said Ken Calvert , Republican member of the House of Representatives .
the leadership errors in CENTCOM range to the top of the organization .
the ten @-@ page report shows detailed problems in 2014 and 2015 in the descriptions and analyses of American efforts to train Iraqi forces .
though it does not provide direct evidence that Obama &apos;s leaders have given instructions to change the reports , it shows how analysts have been exposed to pressure from their prerogatives to draw a more optimistic picture of the threat to the Islamic State , also known as ISIS or ISIL .
&quot; during the first half of 2015 , many Central Command press releases , opinions , and statements before Congress were significantly more positive than the facts , &quot;
for example , a CENTCOM member publicly announced that a military reconquest of Mossuls could begin in April or May 2015 .
Mossul , Iraq &apos;s second largest city , remains under the control of the Islamic State .
said Mike Pompeo , Republican Congressman from Kansas .
from mid @-@ 2014 to mid @-@ 2015 , central command leaders changed intelligence reports to downplay ISIS &apos;s risk in Iraq .
Republicans launched the Task Force after they were admitted that analysts were concerned about manipulating reports on the Islamic State .
the report published on Thursday will be supplemented by more detailed information while the investigation will continue .
in addition , further CENTCOM reports are under way by the General Inspector of Defence .
democratic members of the intelligence committee published their own findings on Thursday , which coincided with some of the conclusions of the Republican Task Force .
&quot; in 2014 and 2015 , CENTCOM created an excessively restricted process for the production of intelligence assessments of ISIL and Iraqi security services , &quot; said the High @-@ Level Democrat in the Committee , Member of the House of Representatives Adam B. Ship .
this process , Mr. Ship said , &quot; delayed the publication of intelligence reports , &quot; damaged morality among analysts and &quot; gave too little room for dissenting opinions . &quot;
but Mr. Ship and the Democrats indicated that they had not found any evidence of intervention by the White House by CENTCOM analysts regarding a &quot; specific political opinion . &quot;
the preliminary results of the Congress &apos;s investigation were published on Tuesday by &quot; The Daily Beast . &quot;
last August , the New York Times reported on investigations by the Pentagon &apos;s general inspector , which were received after complaints from CENTCOM analysts .
Cmdr. Patrick Evans , a Pentagon press officer , stated in an opinion that the Ministry of Defence would not comment on Congressional reports , while the investigation of the general inspector was still under way .
but he also said that &quot; experts sometimes have very divergent views on the interpretation of complex data , and that the intelligence services and the Ministry of Defence welcome a controversial discussion of these important issues of national defense . &quot;
the investigation has repercussions beyond the issue of a successful US @-@ led air campaign in Iraq and Syria ( a claim that is now being made by a growing number of defense officials ) .
but last year &apos;s accusations raised the question of how President Obama can rely on the Central Command for honest assessments of military operations in Iraq , Afghanistan , Libya , and other crisis regions .
the criticism of secret information about the Islamic State is reminiscent of incidents of more than ten years ago , when a CENTCOM analyst , Gregory Hooker , wrote a document about how the then George W. Bush administration , contrary to the recommendations of many analysts , saw only a small occupying force in Iraq and left little time to think about the invasion in 2003 .
Mr. Hooker also played a key role in the uprising against the current coverage of the Islamic State .
last year , the team around Mr. Hooker , according to government officials , found that , contrary to the government &apos;s statements , aerial strikes against refineries held by the Islamic State would not have a significant impact on the financial situation of the terrorist group , as these provisional refineries would have started operating to sell oil on the black market .
this insight was not published , however , reported to the Times in September .
Centcoms then commander Gen. Lloyd J. Austin III was criticized by members of the legislature for his excessively positive assessment of the war situation during a hearing before the Senate .
general Austin retired in April and was replaced by Joseph L. Votel at the Central Command .
