Greenland shark : the oldest vertebrate is almost 400 years old
rare sight .
Greenland sharks are mostly used only in winter .
this Hai was allowed to return to the sea after an investigation on board the Sanna research ship .
he was born in 1624 and swim with about 1 km / h through the North Atlantic - until today .
Greenland sharks are only given 150 years of age .
the Greenland shark sweeps along the bottom of the North Atlantic , reaching an average of just 1,220 metres .
only when it arrives , the 5 @-@ meter long animal accelerates to a saturated 2.6 km / h - and is half as fast as a seal at this maximum speed .
however , this slow lifestyle seems to be a recipe for a long @-@ term age .
Julius Nielsen of the University of Copenhagen and his colleagues report in the journal &quot; Science &quot; in any case a Greenland shark that could be 392 years old .
&quot; madness , &quot; comments Alexander Scheulein from the Max Planck Institute for demographic research in Rostock , this life span , which represents a world record for vertebrates .
although the evolutionary biologist had long believed that Greenland haired .
there was no evidence .
Greenland sharks are hard to observe , after all , they live mainly in the Arctic Ocean off the sparsely populated coasts of Canada , Greenland , Norway and Spitsbergen .
because they prefer water temperatures around six degrees Celsius , they usually only appear on the surface in winter .
researchers know little about Greenland &apos;s lifestyle .
they saw their temporal speed when they placed six animals in front of Spitsbergen with a transmitter .
prey still do this sharks : in the stomach of an animal , researchers found the remains of a seal , another had lured the jaw bone of a young polar bear .
they may hunt slaughtering animals or patrol on the bottom of the icefall and seek carcasses that fall down from higher water layers .
Julius Nielsen and his colleagues have now investigated 28 Greenland sharks , which caught fishermen off Greenland between 2010 and 2013 or Spitsbergen as by @-@ catch from the depths of the North Atlantic .
the smallest hair was just 81 centimetres long , while the largest 502 centimetres were measured .
to determine the age of the animals , they analyzed the lens core of the hair using the carbon 14 method .
this center of the eye lens is created even before the birth of the hair , the proteins contained therein are not renewed later .
the two smallest sharks had remarkably large carbon @-@ 14 in the lens core .
their birth was supposed to be after the early 1960 &quot; s , when nuclear weapons attempts drove larger quantities of this radioactive carbon into the atmosphere .
on the other hand , the lens core contained a small surplus of carbon @-@ 14 from the nuclear weapons tests in the 220 centimetres length of third @-@ smallest animal , so it should have celebrated its 50th birthday in its 2012 investigation .
on the other hand , all major Greenland sharks had normal quantities of carbon @-@ 14 in their linchpin , resulting from cosmic radiation in the atmosphere .
indeed , for a 493 centimetre long Greenland shark , the carbon footprint showed an age of 335 years , while the record shark with 502 centimetres is likely to be 392 years old .
it was known that Greenland @-@ shark females will only be raised when they are longer than four metres .
now the researchers could assign an age to the length .
as one of the animals with 392 centimetres probably stood on the threshold of sexual maturity and its age was determined at 156 years , Greenland &apos;s hair can obviously be reproduced at least one and a half centuries .
that , too , is likely to be a world record for vertebral animals .
it is no coincidence that such methusal systems live mainly in icy waters .
the record holder , a 211 @-@ year @-@ old Greenland whale , in whose bacon stood at the neck of a 120 @-@ year @-@ old Harpunenspitze , was also caught in Alaska .
due to low temperatures , the organism of the animals living there often runs on asparagus .
so they mature later - and older .
in addition , in order to keep warm in the cold water , animals are often particularly large .
because the volume grows much faster than its surface , which causes the animal to lose heat .
the heat loss of a gram of mouse is therefore much greater than a gram of elephant .
another advantage : they have fewer enemies .
&quot; a smaller animal lives more dangerous and should focus on having as many offspring as possible as soon as possible , &quot; explains the evolutionary biologist Scheulein .
a very large animal should invest its resources in a long life .
