Trump &apos;s critics , including the 2012 Republican presidential candidate Mitt Romney , have already made it clear that his refusal raises questions about assets , his donations to charitable organizations , his business practices , and various other ties , especially Russia .
Clinton has already grasped the issue and published a video on the Internet on Friday , in which senior Republicans are calling on Trump to publish his tax declaration .
on Thursday she also raised the issue during a speech on the economy in Michigan .
&quot; he refuses to do what every other presidential candidate has done in recent decades and to publish his tax declarations . &quot; she said .
politico has reported that Trump paid no or very little tax during the 1990 &quot; s , and an economic journalist from the New York Times quoted a number of tax lawyers and tax advisers on Friday , saying that this may still be the case .
federal taxes have become an issue in the campaign .
Clinton supports a scheme named after the billionaire and investor Warren Buffett that would ensure that people who earn more than USD 1 million pay a tax rate of at least 30 % .
President Obama also supports the proposal .
during an election campaign for Hillary Clinton last week in Omaha , Nebraska , Buffett , whose home country is Berkshire Hathaway , called for Trump to meet to exchange tax returns .
Buffett said that he was also subject to an IRS tax test , and Trump was afraid of voters , not tax authorities .
Clinton &apos;s campaign published tax returns back until 2007 .
the Clintons now living in Chappaqua , New York , paid an average effective federal tax rate of about 32 % between 2007 and 2014 and an effective combined tax rate of about 40.5 % .
the 2015 Clinton tax declaration showed that it received only USD 100 of its income as a reward , unlike most Americans .
their main asset was a low @-@ cost index fund , from which the Clinton dividends and earnings of USD 109,000 were taxed .
