future of the merger of Portland as a result of the abolition of the energy contract
the future of Portland &apos;s aluminium meltdown in Victoria - as well as hundreds of workers &quot; jobs - is at stake , as the plant operator will terminate the energy supply contract and thus end all supply contracts , as the supplier notified .
this step follows the decision by the government in Victoria earlier this year not to grant further subsidies to the operation of the plant .
a 20 @-@ year subsidy expires in November .
up to 2000 jobs are at stake in the Alcoa plant in Portland .
no less than 2000 jobs - direct and indirect - could be at risk of closure .
moreover , domino effects may occur , as meltdown consumes about 10 % of Victoria &apos;s total power generation .
in 2014 , Alcoa closed Point Henry , leading to the closure of the Anglesea power plant last year .
Alcoa &apos;s merger in Portland is losing money and risking closure .
this step follows years of speculation about the future of the plant , originally as a result of the strong Australian dollar and most recently because of the electricity price for the plant .
AGL , which supplies the large aluminium melting plant with its Loy Yang A power plant in Latrobe Valley , announced that three other owners would terminate their contracts .
the plant is mainly owned by a joint venture between Alcoa and Alumina , of which the Chinese company CITIC and the Japanese Marubeni Corp hold smaller shares .
&quot; AGL assumes that the plant will continue to operate in Portland , which means further physical demand for electricity through melting , &quot;
AGL continued to say that the contracts were so @-@ called &quot; collateral transactions &quot; which should have entered into force from November 2016 .
the contracts have a 12 @-@ month notice period so that they will end in 2017 .
&quot; therefore AGL assumes that the contracts will contribute 17 to revenue in fiscal year , &quot; said the electricity supplier .
all potential effects on AGL revenues from GJ 18 onwards are currently limited by forecasts of strong futures markets for wholesale electricity prices .
AGL announced that it had already written off the value of the contracts in its annual accounts of $ 187 million in &quot; anticipation of termination . &quot;
Alcoa said that the decision to cancel the contracts did not adversely affect the &quot; ability of Alcoas ... to operate the melting plant or to guarantee electricity supply to the melting plant . &quot;
the US company said that it had concluded a 20 @-@ year contract with Loy Yang in 2010 , which should have entered into force from November this year , even though it is still guilty of explaining why it resigned from the Treaty .
analysts warn against the possible closure of Portland in Victoria and Tomago plant near Newcastle because of the industry &apos;s poor economic conditions .
referring to the analysts &quot; statements earlier this week , the Head of Operations Stephen Mikkelsen said that Portland uses about 600 megawatts and tomago every year about 900 megawatts of electricity .
if both plants were to disappear from the market , this would mean a significant reduction in demand on the &#91; electricity market &#93; .
and for us as a generator of electricity , that would not be good , &quot; he said .
