Nokia 9000 Communicator : the first smartphone
e @-@ mail and Internet in Zeitlupe : 20 years ago Nokia Communicator entered the market .
today , the successors dominate the world - its manufacturer experienced a disaster .
the device was almost half a kilogram and was more than four times as heavy as an iPhone 5 .
it was thicker and bigger , so it was not well in hand .
on the contrary , it was pretty knowledgeable .
the built @-@ in memory was initially eight megabytes , which would now be enough for about two high resolution selffies .
an iPhone is now delivered with at least 16 gigabytes .
the Nokia 9000 Communicator came into business exactly 20 years ago , on 15 August 1996 - and it was the first smartphone .
for a few euros lovers can still buy the equipment on the Internet , but they are somehow from the Stone Age of the Internet .
however , 20 years ago , the Communicator was a sensation .
the Finnish mobile phone manufacturer announced the product a few months earlier at the Cebit computer fair in Hanover as an &quot; office in the western pocket format . &quot;
in fact , the new mobile phone could achieve a lot for then standards : SMS and e @-@ mails could be sent and received , even by fax was to reach the Communicator .
even access to web pages was possible via HTML browser , albeit slowly .
a calculator was available , a digital address book and an electronic calendar .
there was a small antenna , and the mobile phone could be folded like a laptop .
then there was a small keyboard and a black and white screen .
the price was quite proud : 2700 D @-@ Mark , i.e. about 1400 Euro .
the average selling price of a smartphone in Germany was 392 euros in 2015 .
no one could predict in August 1996 that the Communicator would become the beginning of the smartphone era .
since then , things have changed .
the smart phones are a success story , though not for Nokia .
the cellular phone business of the Finns experienced an unprecedented disaster and was finally sold and processed to Microsoft .
today the market is dominated by suppliers , all of whom came much later than Nokia .
being always online , this is today for many people everyday .
in 2015 , there were nearly two billion smartphone users worldwide .
some 1.4 billion devices were sold , of which 555 million are owned by Samsung and Apple .
worldwide sales of the equipment are about EUR 400 billion .
this includes the well @-@ being of the numerous app providers and telecommunications companies .
a whole industry has developed around the smartphone .
the decisive breakthrough to the mass market came only in early 2007 , when Apple &apos;s chief Steve Jobs announced the launch of the iPhones at the Mac World .
he promised three devices in one : a music player , a phone and an Internet communicator , everything easy to use by touch screen .
Apple &apos;s winning move began , and today the iPhone is the group &apos;s most important product .
Nokia , Motorola and Blackberry , who dominated the market , had the afterthought .
she finally disappeared , Blackberry has to fight .
Apple and Asian suppliers like Samsung now have the say .
the smartphone is a matter of course 20 years after its invention .
on average every German now looks at his mobile phone 88 times a day .
&quot; we must all learn to get rid of the smartphone , &quot; said Janina Kugel , in the Siemens Board of Directors responsible for staff .
permanent accessibility is now considered a curse and blessing at the same time .
