NASA Climate Model : Venus was once habitable
according to the projections of a new NASA climate model , Venus was probably once habitable .
scientists at the Goddard Institute for Space Studies of NASA developed a model to discover the past of Venus using tools and algorithms similar to those of climate researchers .
the model was designed to determine whether the Venus , with its hot , water @-@ free surface and CO2 @-@ dense atmosphere , could once have shown earth @-@ like conditions .
scientists previously suggested that the slow change of Venus could be explained by its dense atmosphere .
but the latest simulation suggests that the Venus could have had a thin , earth @-@ like atmosphere , and that it was slowly moving forward .
the model also illuminated the topography of the early Venus .
the planet probably had more dry areas than de Earth , but once had enough water and geographical variability to house lives and protect against rapid evaporation .
the early Venus also benefited from a sun that was 30 % matt .
&quot; in the Giss model simulation the slow rotation of Venus exposes its day side of the sun for almost two months , &quot; explained Giss Scientist Anthony Del Genio in a press release .
this warms the surface and produces rain that creates a thick layer of clouds , which looks like a rain umbrella to shield the surface from much of the sun &apos;s heat .
the result is average temperatures that are some degrees cooler than those of the Earth today .
the model produced a history of Venus that resembles the evolution previously suspected by planetary researchers .
although it was probably habitable , the Venus -- over several billion years --was exposed to too much heat and ultraviolet light .
their oceans darkened and their water vapour was burnt away from ultraviolet light .
when their hydrogen escaped , only a thick atmosphere of carbon dioxide with a lethal greenhouse effect remained - the Venus that we know today .
researchers shared the results of their new Venus climate model in Geophysical Research Letters .
