Kepler measures rotation rate of stars in the stellar clusters of the Plejads
the latest mission with the Kepler Space telescope has helped astronomers to collect the most complete catalogue of rotation rates among the stars of the Plejads .
the new data help astronomers understand why stars rotate to different rates in the star clusters and in what context the rotation periods are linked to the planetary creation .
&quot; we hope to learn more about the relationship between the mass of a star , its age , and even the history of its solar system , &quot; said Luisa Rebull , a scientist at Caltech &apos;s Infrared Processing and Analysis Center in Pasadena , in a press release .
the archaeological site of the Plejaden lies 445 light years from Earth .
many stars in this clubhouse , created around 125 million years ago , now reach adulthood .
you are now turning quickly .
at peak rotational rates , these mature stars emit large amounts of stars .
as these winds travel through the magnetic fields of the stars , they have a dampening effect on the stars .
when an asterisk is ageing , its rotation rate begins to slow .
Kepler measures the rotation rate of each star by recognizing the time between the appearance of a recognizable star , such as sunshades .
the latest catalogue of rotation rates indicates that more massive stars are turning slower than less massive stars .
Rebull compares the stars with dancers , with larger stars turning slower pirouettes than smaller ones .
&quot; in the &quot; Ballet &quot; of the Plejaden we see that slow Rotors tend to be more massive , whereas faster Rotors tend to be very bright stars , &quot; Rebull said .
as the star clusters of the Plejads are so close , it serves as an ideal cosmic laboratory to compare stellar qualities such as rotation rates .
&quot; the star clusters of Plejaden offers an anchor for theoretical models of stellar rotation in both directions , younger and older , &quot; said Rebull .
there is still a lot to be learned about , such as how , when , and why stars slow down their rotation rates and hang their &quot; dance shoes . &quot;
Rebull and her colleagues have reported in detail in three newspaper reports on their latest analysis of the reddening rates of Plejaden , which will soon be published in the Astronomical Journal .
