data Dog : so perfide blackmail hackers
developers of blackmail malware currently target companies - and are successful in doing so .
according to a recent survey of malware defence specialists Malwarebytes among 540 companies in North America , the United Kingdom and Germany , 40 % of the companies surveyed have been at least once , in part several times , victims of an attack with Erpresser software .
in Germany , almost 20 % of companies were already the target of ransomware blackmail .
40 % of the victims willingly paid the lion &apos;s money requested by the perpetrators in order to be able to reuse the systems and data that were attacked .
according to Malwarebytes &quot; observations , the perpetrators are increasingly specializing in attacks on corporate networks .
if they are successful , the potentially extortionating lion &apos;s money will be much higher than private users .
&quot; we are currently seeing a terrifying rapid evolution of the malware , &quot; explains Malwarebytes chief Marcin Kleczynski in talks with the &quot; world . &quot;
in 2008 , most malware programs were designed to send advertising .
then the perpetrators discovered blackmail software for themselves .
first of all , private users were the target , but the shift to company attacks has been made terribly fast in recent months .
Ransomware works on a simple pattern : once active on a victim &apos;s computer , it looks specifically for recently modified files such as Word , Excel or database files , and archives of images and videos .
these files encrypt the Ransomware and permanently delete the originals .
afterwards , the software presents the demands of the blackmail .
to get the final key code to the files , the victims must transfer money - mostly in the form of the Cryptocurrency Bitcoin .
however , where private users are at stake in the personal photo database , companies are concerned with sensitive customer data or project databases , without which production will stop .
accordingly , the damage is higher if a Ransomware strikes .
22 % of German companies concerned reported sales losses due to Ransomware , 13 % had to interrupt business completely , in one case people were in danger of life .
in Germany , hospitals have been victims of attacks whose patients may be threatened by the loss of medical records .
&quot; we always say to the victims : does not pay , it only promotes the problem , &quot; says Kleczynski .
but 80 @-@ 90 % of companies that pay get their data back .
managers find it difficult to reject the perpetrators &quot; demands in the face of deadlock in operation .
hackers , in turn , know this and try to build a good reputation .
in a recent study , F @-@ Secure security researchers have examined user areas and contact with the blacksmiths and come to the conclusion : the perpetrators are actually trying to build a kind of customer service to collect more money .
they explain to their victims via chat how to pay via Bitcoin , set up or decrypt free support websites .
and when private individuals are redeemed after payments of a few hundred euros , companies sometimes have to negotiate hard and pay five @-@ digit sums to get their data back unencrypted .
given the potentially high and relatively risk @-@ free profits from ransomware blackmail , hackers are becoming more and more professional and share the work , says security expert Chester Wisniewski of the antivirus provider Sophos : &quot; a single person can write a ransomware about a week . &quot;
however , it is more likely that these are three or four people .
the programmers then sell their malicious software in the form of a software module to the actual blackmail .
the previous malware kits were created by buying the malware themselves , advice and additional tools for a unique fixed price between $ 1000 and $ 10,000 .
&quot; included in the package is an adjustment tool so that smaller configurations , appearance and branding can be changed , &quot; says Wisniewski .
the blacksmiths then look for more hackers to spread the newly purchased software among the victims .
we live in a service economy .
so you log into one of the forums in the underground , buy the set from a criminal and order another to install the software on as many PCs as possible .
payment is made per computer .
&quot; usually the criminals then commission spammers to spread , &quot; explains Wisniewski .
the risk of Ransomware is now known to many companies that are better able to protect their data .
more than 50 % of company IT managers in the Malwarebytes survey trust in being able to resist Ransomware using file back @-@ ups and scanner software .
accordingly , the perpetrators are already pursuing new strategies .
&quot; if the encryption of data alone is no longer a sufficient threat to successful retrieval , the perpetrators risk publishing sensitive data such as customer lists or price calculations , &quot; explains Malwarebytes CEO Marcin Kleczynski .
this makes the damage potential much higher than before depending on the type of data .
in future , the perpetrators could also put completely new targets on the Internet of Things .
at the Hacker Conference Defcon , security researchers demonstrated how to control a thermostat connected to the Internet .
in the middle of winter the activation of such a blocked heating may well be worth a ransom .
if the perpetrators then block a whole production line in a factory instead of heating in the future , Ransomware could also become an issue in the industry 4.0 .
one for all cases
Honda HR @-@ V is flexible and customizable
in the small HR @-@ V Honda wants to pack everything : a little SUV , a little coupÃ© and also the versatility of a minivan .
