someone sprayed on the facade of a grey house .
compared to a lidl , which is soon to be demolished , a house with high windows and 133 new apartments will be built here by 2017 .
however , articles about this &quot; trendy district , &quot; as the responsible real estate company Friedrichshain calls it , are mainly illustrated with burning cars in recent weeks .
the reason is the house number 94 : once occupied , residents now have rental contracts , but on the ground floor there are still rooms and are used for events .
since the beginning of the year , the Berlin interior senator Henkel , in particular , has repeatedly argued in favour of a police crackdown on the project , calling the area &quot; no @-@ go zone &quot; for police officers and 94 as the starting point for autonomous violence .
after , on 22 June , the rooms on the ground floor , the Kadterschmiede , had been cleared with 300 police officers , the police patrolled official statements for three weeks , with 30 to 40 officials and three team cars on the ground , blocked parts of the street and prevented visitors from entering the house with number 94 .
in the meantime the rooms were renovated on behalf of the unknown owners .
on July 13 , a Berlin administrative court ruled that the evacuation had been illegal , and one day later police and construction workers withdrew under the anguish of sympathizers and residents .
on this summer afternoon the street works peacefully : parents walk with children , people sit on the sidewalk in front of the houses in the sun , others talk about spÃ¤ti .
there is a primary school and kindergarten nearby .
left @-@ wing violence is not the main concern of many residents : Kerstin Neugebauer , who has been living in Kiev since 1999 , and Jana * , who is raising three children here , are above all generalized by the police presence .
with the inhabitants of the house projects , they share the concern about increasing rent and genetic modification .
it does not sound like a jaw that the majority wanted to secure police protection from vandalizing left .
the tomb that the Berlin interior senator and the police set up between house leaders and their neighbors does not seem to exist .
Friedrichshain in the east of Berlin was actually a traditional working district , which still has a low average income and high risk of poverty compared to the rest of the city .
in 1990 many houses were occupied in the former GDR , including almost the entire Mainz street near Rigaer .
while Mainz had been cleared in a real street battle under a large police force , many of the Rigaer projects were legalised and are still inhabited by the people who occupied them 26 years ago .
at the same time , in recent years , the district has become increasingly a magnet for tourists and election connoisseurs from all over the world : with them , residents of the GDR and former house occupiers now share their pines .
this can also be seen in the case of renting , which since 2009 has increased by almost 60 % for new renting .
many of the new buildings in the Rigaer are being attacked as symbols of this development : they are recognized by shelves or newly cut facades , which have been beaten with colours .
no other road has been mentioned so often this year , along with the words &apos; left @-@ wing violence &apos; .
one reason that not all neighbours see this as a problem may be that they are not necessarily affected by crime : crimes such as personal injury , according to statistics , are almost exclusively directed against policemen .
most of the crimes are damage to property , which tends to hit the new buildings and newly renovated houses .
for Kerstin Neugebauer , who has been living in a rental house for 17 years next to the controversial 94 , there can be no question of uncertainty .
as far as violence is concerned , it is reassuring : the people of 94 are their neighbours , who have certainly not been .
even the famous burning cars no longer exist in the Rigaer .
for the studied architect , her street is not a criminal focal point , on the contrary : &quot; here you help each other , live together on the street and get more with each other than anywhere else . &quot;
Neugebauer has consciously moved to Rigaer StraÃe - and remained .
that is why it was so important for the residents to get back to their streets : the police , the politics and the media , all of which suddenly claimed the power of interpretation over the district in July .
but , in the eyes of residents like Neugebauer , the road continues to be taken away from them : by reckless new buildings in former building blocks , which drive away the old inhabitants .
&quot; after all , these are real estate properties that are not of interest to many here - here people who are not so well looked after live , &quot; she says .
&quot; I absolutely cannot endorse violence and destruction . &quot;
but what should we do if someone never hears ?
